column1: 175026;instagram;2019-01-09 17:07:39;FALSE;"trusting other people after you've been abused is difficult. what may surprise you is how difficult it is to trust yourself.
people can tell you all day that it wasn't your fault
column2: but you have a deep mistrust of yourself.

column1: you don't trust your skill of judging the character of others
column2: and you don't trust your own strength.

column1: let me tell you with complete certainty: your abuse was not about you.
let me tell you something else: you have more strength in your pinky finger than most will ever need to muster.
don't believe me? that's because the words and actions of your abuser has caused you to fully believe that you don't deserve better.
check out my moving forward after abuse online course by clicking on the link in my bio.

column1: 175059;instagram;2019-01-09 17:30:43;FALSE;"a few years ago i made the biggest change ever in my life by deciding to break free from a toxic relationship that was killing me physically
column5: i've had to adjust and survive as a single mother of three along with juggling day to day obstacles. but
column6: i learned how to make it work and have been living a happier and healthier life since. now
column7: i'm no stranger to overcoming challenges and leaving a toxic relationship was just one of the many struggles i've had to overcome. ***

column1: join on january 16 @ 7pm est for my free webinar (linktree in bio to sign up) where we will discuss the tools and resources i used to walk away from a toxic relationship

column2: i’d like to acknowledge the women who have survived abuse of any kind! we can all judge and formulate opinions that make sense to us but to be so insensitive to the recent outcries from women who have survived abuse
column3: especially our black woman is disgusting and a real reason why so many don’t speak out when they’ve been abused. while statistics have proven this
column4: i’m speaking from experience. when i was 16 i was sexually abused by an older guy. i didn’t tell my mother or anyone
column5: in fact i waited till i was 21 and i decided that i no longer wanted this to burden or hinder me. i no longer wanted to blame or belittle myself for being a cute girl and wearing short skirts. i no longer wanted to believe that i was “asking for it” as so many tend to say when one of us go through such trauma. (no one was there to hear me scream no
column7: fight and cry!!) but even then i was unable to speak about the event or the person who had done it and dance was my way of release and healing. i developed the platform diamond in the rough in 2012 to be a voice for the voiceless and to provide a way of healing through dance for myself and others because sometimes trauma don’t allow us to find the words to correctly articulate and express pain. moving forward as i reinvent diamond in the rough
column8: i am adding mentoring resources to not only help aid mental development through art such as dance but leadership development as well. ➰

column1: if you know anyone or if you are someone that has survived abuse

column1: 175137;instagram;2019-01-09 18:36:33;FALSE;"once upon a time there was a girl named brandi…
brandi was a fat girl. and she was shy.
brandi got picked on and bullied at school.
and she had too many #metoo moments growing up.
brandi ran away as a young teen. (but returned home later that day cause she was a dumb teenager 😂)

brandi met some friends that showed her a different way. they showed her what it felt like to be accepted as she was. they showed her what #support felt like. they showed her what a family feels like.
so brandi started exercising. she started eating better and reading and learning.
then one day she gave in to the pressures around her and got married.
brandi slowly disappeared over those 10 years…
then one day she woke the fuck up. (losing a #beloved family member will force you in a cruel way to take stock on your own life.)
brandi took a leap of faith in herself and got the hell out of that dead marriage.
she stepped back on to this ride we call life…
she loved waking up and feeling and experiencing and #living once again.

column2: but brandi promised herself that she’ll never go back to that miserable way of just existing. she wants more than that. and she knows she deserves more than that.

column1: 175179;instagram;2019-01-09 19:24:54;FALSE;"this is me when i was 20. here’s her story:

i decided to come out and share my act of courage against sexual abuse and sexual harassment. i recorded my story and posted it on my youtube channel to share my experience and to help empower others to share their experiences. https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sb998l9ugq8&feature=youtu.be (link in my bio @adventuresacross) i feel like what happened to me in college happens to a lot of young women and i will not tolerate it anymore. no means no!

column2: i was in an uncomfortable situation where i was stuck at a guy's house who wanted to have sex with me. i said no over and over again for four hours and felt like i didn't have a choice to call someone else to pick me up. he wouldn't take me home
column3: and i felt very uncomfortable calling my parents because of their views on sex at the time. looking back
column4: it would have been smarter to call my parents but in reality he got what he wanted.

column1: i honor what happened to me because it gave me a voice to speak out about this. i am not a victim
column2: i am an empowered woman here to help other women find their empowered voice. this disrespect towards women needs to stop! i especially saw it while i was in college
column3: how guys would get girls drunk just for some action. that is bullshit. women deserve more respect than that
column4: we are all equal humans you know!! i encourage you to submit your act of courage to the illuminate website. we're collecting 1000 stories to spread awareness and to stop the inequality of humans. find the details here: http://illuminatefilmfestival.com/acts-of-courage

column3: listening to common the rapper talk about how black women aren’t believed vs white women.... i am not a man hater .. i believe abuse occurs from both sides. however

column1: 175223;instagram;2019-01-09 19:59:09;FALSE;i wasn’t sure if i wanted to write an article on this topic or not. there are a lot of things i don’t know about this man and the stories that have been told about him.  there are a few things i do know via hearsay but nothing solid.  honestly i feel sorry for this man and his victims.  i feel sorry for him because i truly feel he needs help and people around him have enabled his behavior.  i have read a few of the past stories about him online over the years and his childhood
column2: and he has suffered sexual abuse and trauma which he has been vocal about.  whats crazy is
column3: many people in his circle including celebrities and fans have took a blind eye to actions that he has and swept them under the rug.  now this document series comes out about him and victims that he has had encounters with are speaking out
column4: but why has it took so long?  shame
column6: or has the #metoo movement allowed us to be more comfortable with speaking out? i believe that many of the parents and young women were star struck
column7: and i am pretty sure wanted to be in the presents of a celebrity or to be chosen as his protege.  people look and love opportunity  and many people will put pride
column8: and self respect aside to obtain it
column9: such as reality tv stars. lets be real – how real is reality tv and how much air time will you get if you are not willing to do something petty or demeaning for ratings?  i look at it the same way

column2: it's about a different kind of freedom. not entrepreneurial freedom
another human being died by her hand. we should not forget the life that was lost.
we cannot lose sight of the fact that a 16-year old child somehow ended up in the bed of a 43-year old man ... who i understand was also a youth religious pastor of some kind.
you have half a brain and you don't even know it. that's what makes being 16 so dangerous.

column1: 175272;instagram;2019-01-09 21:09:37;FALSE;"it’s a new year. time to set new goals
setting goals can bring up all kinds of drama.⠀

column2: i got an email from a coach i follow. @susanhyatt 💖 she shared a process for setting 2019 goals
column3: and i instantly had a wave of anxiety.⠀

column2: and for a lot of my clients
column3: that anxiety comes from a fear of failure – from saying publicly “i want this” and then not getting it.⠀

column1: but it also comes from a fear of success. because change of any kind – even if it’s change you want – can feel stressful. not to mention that other people have higher expectations of you as you rise to higher levels.⠀
i was chatting with my friend @drmichellemazur about this goal anxiety and she unknowingly articulated what i ask my clients to do when they set goals: ⠀
change them from smart goals (which i personally think are ridiculous and counterproductive in most cases) to mindful daily habits.⠀
if you’re not familiar with smart goals
column2: it’s an acronym that stands for specific measurable actionable realistic timed.⠀

column1: what daily habits does a person like the one i want to be have?⠀

column2: what does a woman who feels energetic and confident every day eat for breakfast?⠀

column1: what does a woman who brings her a game to her work and/or her family do every evening?⠀
what does a woman who runs her own business do every day before she gets to the office? what does she do in the middle of her day? what about at the end?⠀
step one: what kind of person do you want to be? who are some real people that exemplify that kind of person? ⠀
step two: what kinds of things does that person do every day?⠀
look for people in your life who you admire and want to be more like; then see if you can figure out some of their daily habits. or ask them if you know them personally!⠀
because that’s where the magic happens: with mindful daily habits.⠀
simple daily habits will get you to your goals much faster than creating anxiety-producing grand plans.⠀

column2: check out the brand new women on the rise podcast episode: reclaiming your dreams with dr. marcia morgan. link in bio.";;en;;@susanhyatt

column5: the book of proverbs speaks with utter clarity as it infuses its readers with transcendent wisdom that is timely and culturally relevant.

column1: when we are tired and weary - we must rest. - physically
every aspect of us needs rest many times over in our lifetimes. have you noticed though...we only allow ourselves this rest when we feel safe! 👀
so many of us who are going through or have been through
column2: the trauma of domestic violence (whether it be physical abuse
column5: or psychological abuse) feel on high alert every minute of every day - in subconscious survival mode for ‘just in case’! even in places or situations that are logically safe to us....our minds cannot escape that feeling of unease
column6: and constantly reverts to survival mode as a knee-jerk reaction to every situation.

column1: and the ‘temptations of the flesh’ that overtakes us many times over
column2: because they are so easy for us to fall into because of our trauma: fear

column1: it’s hard!!! and it’s tiring! and it’s confusing!!! those who know - will know! this feeling of ‘unsafe’ within us
column3: is hard to explain...and even harder to un-train in our minds....but in him

column2: and through god....is the peace and love that we have been seeking! in that
column3: we can rest our weary souls. in his love and peace...we can finally feel safe! 💖

column1: коктейлът bloody mary е по всяка вероятност приготвен за първи път в harry's bar (париж).според една от версиите
column2: коктейла е сервирал за първи път френският барман фернандо ""пит"" петио още през 1920 - 1921 г. в парижкия бар ""харис"". той за първи път смесва водка
column5: пипер и уорчестър сос. така се получава станалия по-късно знаменит коктейл ""блъди мери"". по-късно
column6: вече в хотел ""сейнт риджис"" в ню йорк
column7: той дооформил коктейла по молба на принц серж соболенски
column9: която за мнозина е съвсем достоверна
column10: този коктейл е бил приготвен от пютио за американския актьор рои бъртън и е бил първо наречен ""bucket of blood"". за парижани коктейлът става популярен няколко години по-късно
column11: след безспорния му успех в сащ.

column1: произходът на името е спорно. според някои
column2: този коктейл дължи името си на мария i тюдорнаречена bloody mary (кървавата мери) тази английска кралица
column4: управлява няколко години и е известна със своята кръвожадност. наречена е така поради своята политика на преследване на протестантите

column1: 175348;instagram;2019-01-09 22:16:57;FALSE;i know that i am always joking around and laughing
column3: i always have a smile on my face when i post a selfie. i’m always happy in my live videos. but
column4: that is perfect example of social media allowing us to put up a front. i put up a front in real life so i am a pro💁🏻‍♀️
column5: this just makes it even easier. but
column6: never compare your life to others
column7: especially on facebook. “comparison is the thief of happiness
column8: ” and we are all on our own
column9: unique journeys. people put out what they want you to see
column10: when the reality is most likely completely different. i honestly do not try to put up a front
column11: and am not being fake. i use laughter as a coping mechanism. most of the time it’s either laugh or cry
column13: it’s really just a way for me to hide my true feelings. i hide all of the pain
column18: and the guilt of all of the things i can’t do for my family because of this crippling illness. that is not how i want the world to see me and if i don’t joke and make fun of myself
column19: i will just crumble. i put up a front for myself! if that makes any sense at all
column20: kind of like “fake it till you make it.” the truth is
column21: most days feel like i’m barely hanging on by a thread
column23: and today is definitely one of those days. so
column24: i decided to post a selfie of the way i truly feel. today
column25: i feel numb and sick. i hate this illness
column26: i hate the person that gave me this crippling disorder. i am not looking for sympathy
column27: many have gone through what i have or worse. i just wanted to share my truth. i hope this helps you to stop comparing and realize that what you see is not always real. don’t worry about me! i am way to strong💪🏼 and stubborn😤 to let this take me down. i have been fighting the fight for nearly 20 years and i’m almost on the other side
column28: i’m almost in a place where i can manage it and not let it effect my quality of life. it will not win💪🏼💪🏼! even on days like today
column29: i see a bright future. i am on the right path

column1: 175358;instagram;2019-01-09 22:54:19;FALSE;"i just watched ""surviving r kelly"". every parent
column4: every american needs to watch it in its entirety. it's available on on demand right now. i intended to watch one episode and ended up binging the entire series. rkelly needs to be erased from the archives of history and needs to be behind bars for the rest of his existence. his former manager and assistant and anyone else who was knowingly complacent should be held accountable. until then

column2: of surviving custody built for survivors. there were many of us. one in her 30s was in such a possessive situation
column3: she became a hoarder in a place with bunks and two drawers. and slept on a mountain of the garbage she collected. there was one who was incredibly violent that escaped truckers. one snuck in a bunch of street drugs and i did not participate but that was interesting
column4: she was my case the place buddy
column6: horrifying and hilarious. couldn't mix street and prescription. other things to help get out. well
column7: if you refuse they would place shots
column8: and then you'd wake up a week later. so the nurse
column10: request the lowest dose and they'll argue
column14: and hold back any reaction. reacting to anything outside of the shower
column15: will raise the dose of whatever the fuck they give you. and know that there is nothing they can give you to solve trauma
column17: and some are symptoms of trauma
column18: but none can be selected in the 5 minutes they see you
column19: so they place something typical on your chart. before they bring papers they sedate you
column20: and no clue on ever having seen them. mental health is about your accountability to know when to walk
column21: while in the 'free' world. don't end up in custody
column22: i'd like to say don't ask for help
column24: that shouldn't be how it is
column26: that might put you in custody. on a lighter subject learning a lot things in different places was good and bad
column27: missed some basic life skills along the way
column28: and learned other things instead. did not know about how tall people aren't older until very late in my short life
column29: thought all the giants were gandalf and like 50
column30: until i talked to someone who was my age and really tall
column31: who knew?! and how dare they spell wednesday like that

175482;instagram;2019-01-10 01:28:42;FALSE;i'm being the best me and living my best life. this is a day by day kinda thing. i just do what works for me and not worry about opinions. fuck it..i'm over 40 and may have lived the longest i will ever live. so this means
column2: today i may spend time alone but tomorrow i may spend time with friends. next week i may choose to travel and the week after i may just chill. some days i may just eat what i want and other days i exercise discipline. one day i may put makeup on and another day i may show up with the natural me. some days i may have a lot to say and other days i may just want to be in silence. the whole point is this...worry less about rules and norms. self care starts here
column3: where you focus on your needs. live your life in a way that pleases you...this is the best life certainly.

column1: 175483;instagram;2019-01-10 01:29:18;FALSE;"shame is a generational coping skill parents use to cope with their lack of self-worth & those diseased parents project their own shame onto their children. it’s an insidious form of emotional abuse because the child takes the parent’s shame on as their own & invents a story in their head that they’re not wanted
shame based families don’t allow freedom of feeling or expression
column2: all are to be shoved down & internalized. they demand perfection & blame others when perfection can’t be achieved. they deny you your truth & deny reality.

column1: these are the type of family where there’s constantly an elephant in the room. “are we ever going to really discuss what’s going on?” nope. you’re not.
watch. some or all of the people in this family system have an addiction of some sorts
column2: are an abuser or are in life long therapy or on psych meds. the shame is eating away at the core of who they are and  is at the core of all addictions

column1: in order to heal from growing up in a shameful family you must get real- you’ve been emotionally abused & it has rewired your brain & your subconscious. you are toxic to yourself by virtue of the environment.
it is imperative that you claim this.

then you must begin to do the painful work of separating you & the messaging you received from your abuser. start listening to that voice in your head & see when it is subconsciously your abuser talking & not really you. start honing into and listening for the voice of your intuition that was either shut down or never developed. if the people who shamed you are not willing to acknowledge the abuse they caused you  or work on their own inadequacies and wounds- cut them out of your life like a cancer. bone
column3: doesn’t matter. a sick person is contagious. period.

column2: &  all about their inability to develop self-worth of their own. separate who you are from the dis-ease of them & know that by your birthright & by god

column1: 175517;instagram;2019-01-10 02:23:14;FALSE;"i didn’t think that watching #survivingrkelly would effect me quite like it has ... even though @milano_alyssa and the folks of the #metoo movement warned that it might. it brought me back to some deep memories and emotions that i rarely tap into any more. particularly because when r kelly was in his prime
column4: too was tangled up in a shit relationship ( if i dare to even call it a relationship) with a narcissist that had about as much concern for women as r kelly has. i was only 19 when i met my abuser. i remember him telling me that “no one would ever love me like he would” which was totally fucked up and distorted
column5: because he clearly didn’t love me one bit. but some how
column7: i had a weakness or insecurity of some sort that he could identify
column8: and take advantage of. much like the strategy of r kelly. edit: i was young
column9: vulnerable and inexperienced. never weak. thx @ally.dobbs ❤️

column1: if you are in a relationship that makes you feel like shit
column2: or if someone makes you believe that you don’t deserve more
column3: then i am proof that it’s all bullshit. if you are with someone that controls you
column4: that lacks #empathy and has a sense of entitlement that exaggerates their own self importance
column5: if your person harms you or forces you to do things you don’t believe in
column7: and don’t look back. i know it’s easier said than done
column8: but never give up. even if you feel helpless
column9: know that you are not. you deserve to live a life free of fear. i am sending you all ❤️ and strength. #muterkelly #survivor #yoga #womenempowerment #womenagainstabuse #endviolenceagainstwomen #staystrong";;en;#survivingrkelly

column1: 175522;instagram;2019-01-10 02:45:15;FALSE;i am sick and tired of all these people out here just killing and eating plants as if they aren’t living creatures with feelings! you guys wouldn’t believe it but people grow plants on giant farms just to eat them! 🤮 how would you like it if someone pulled you out of the ground or off a tree and ate you? huh???? how would you like it if i just walked up in your house all willy nilly and pulled your ficus out of it’s pot and made myself a salad. you wouldn’t would you? someone has to do something!!! so i’m taking a stand for the plants and just eating meat 100% of the time. unless i’m drunk and i want some edamame or some shit. or unless i don’t feel like it. or if eating a plant is going to get me laid. but the rest of the time i’m taking the moral high ground and really committing on this shit. #savetheplants #metoo #selflove #bodypositivity #intermittentfasting #brandonwiththegoodhair #keto #carnivore #nevergiveup #treatmyficusasyouwanttobetreated #bethelight;;en;#savetheplants

column1: 175531;instagram;2019-01-10 02:50:58;FALSE;i am home//then i am not// i am sān zàng on his journey to the west//getting the wisdom of the west//i am home//then i am not//the bed covers a half of my body and my feet are always cold//without the warmth of the earth of home//i am always cold//even seeing the red lanterns can’t provide me with a little comfort//my roof is always the sky and my dream is always dotted with stars - constellations of a city that i used to call home
column2: like home home//like many before me
column3: they built a community of sān zàngs who have lost their horses and the western wisdoms on the bamboo scrolls are too heavy//so they settled like dust

column1: 175543;instagram;2019-01-10 03:17:50;FALSE;trigger warning: i don’t know what compelled me to make this post but i need to get it off my chest. a few of you know i’m a victim of sexual assault but for those of you who don’t i’ve been sexually assaulted five times. 4 times by people i knew and once on new years by a random guy. i have a really heavy heart and i put most people above me even strangers. i’ll go the extra mile for people i don’t even know. i’m not making this post to be like “why me” i’m making it to spread awareness that this can happen to people you wouldn’t expect. i’m lucky enough to be in tune with the universe and understand that i’ll be okay even when shit hits the fan but i know for a lot of people that’s not the case. people feel alone
column4: degraded. the lack of tenderness we give our victims is wrong. so i’m just here to say anyone of any color
column8: etc. i am here for you because i know how it feels to be on the other side of the spectrum. the side where people look at you as if you provoked it. the side where people question what you were wearing or what you were doing before asking how you’re feeling. even today i feel as though the people i call my close friends won’t understand my emotions so i keep to myself and i try to be the peace maker

column1: 175567;instagram;2019-01-10 03:51:49;FALSE;i knew going in that “blurred lines: rethinking sex
column3: and consent on campus” was going to be a tough read. vanessa grigoriadis wrote a chunk of it about wesleyan during the years i was a student there
column4: and some of the activists and survivors she profiles are my peers. grigoriadis herself went to wesleyan
column5: but a decade or so before
column6: and her depiction of the school i know is a funhouse mirror of stereotypes
column7: and not always kind ones. she asks important questions in the book about how we can teach consent
column8: the role fraternities play in emboldening rape on campus
column11: when women are most likely to be assaulted. but her tone was at times condescending toward her younger counterparts and it made me frustrated with the book as a whole—while i don’t disagree with most of her conclusions
column12: she came across as callous and mean-spirited on occasion. young survivors of sexual violence initiated a massive cultural change that laid the groundwork for the #metoo movement
column13: as grigoriadis says. to claim that some young people are “a bit too interested in classifying themselves as survivors” as if it’s a trend is... not a good look.  i’m glad i read blurred lines and learned a lot but i wouldn’t recommend it. #rapeculture #consent #blurredlines #sexpositive #bookstagram #bookstagrammer #books📚 #bookish #booksofinstagram #feministreads #booknerd #womenwriters #wesleyan #banfrats #greeklife;;en;#MeToo

column1: a japanese men's magazine has had to issue an apology after publishing a list ranking universities on how easy it is to convince female students to have sex at drinking parties. the list in the issue of the weekly magazine spa! prompted outrage. one woman launched a campaign calling for an apology and for the article to be removed.

it referred to the practice of gyaranomi - drinking parties where men pay women to attend. the article in the 25 december issue said the parties were popular among female college students and included an interview with the developer of an app intended to help men and women find potential attendees. ""we would like to apologise for using sensational language to appeal to readers about how they can become intimate with women and for creating a ranking... with real university names... that resulted in a feature that may have offended readers
column2: the magazine said in a statement. ""on issues that involve sex
column3: we will do what we can as a magazine to listen to various opinions

column1: the article mentioned five colleges where students were ""easily available"" at drinking parties
column2: and described how to ""coax"" women and judge whether a woman was sexually available based on her clothing and appearance

column1: the petition started by kazuna yamamoto on change.org had been supported by more than 33
column2: 000 people on tuesday. ""japan will be having the first g20 summit this year
column4: and it is ridiculous for an article such as this to be published. it's not funny at all
column5: she wrote on the petition page. ""i would like to fight so that
column6: especially on public articles such as this one
column8: objectifying and disrespecting women would stop. we demand shuukan spa take this article back and apologise
column9: and promise to not use objectifying words to talk about women""

column2: i’d like to acknowledge the woman who have survived abuse of any kind! we can all judge and formulate opinions that make sense to us but to be so insensitive to the recent outcries from women who have survived abuse
column3: especially our black woman is disgusting and a real reason why so many don’t speak out when they’ve been abused. while statistics have proven this
column4: i’m speaking from experience. when i was 16 i was sexually abused by an older guy. i didn’t tell my mother or anyone
column5: in fact i waited till i was 21 and i decided that i no longer wanted this to burden or hinder me. i no longer wanted to blame or belittle myself for being a cute girl and wearing short skirts. i no longer wanted to believe that i was “asking for it” as so many tend to say when one of us go through such trauma. (no one was there to hear me scream no
column7: fight and cry!!) but even then i was unable to speak about the event or the person who had done it and dance was my way of release and healing. i developed the platform diamond in the rough in 2012 to be a voice for the voiceless and to provide a way of healing through dance for myself and others because sometimes trauma don’t allow us to find the words to correctly articulate and express pain. moving forward as i reinvent diamond in the rough
column8: i am adding mentoring resources to not only help aid mental development through art such as dance but leadership development as well. ➰

column2: you free to contact me d1.nechelle@gmail.com

column1: 175636;instagram;2019-01-10 05:40:37;FALSE;"""for the first time in its 127-year history
column2: the american psychological association has issued guidelines to help psychologists specifically address the issues of men and boys — and the document features a warning.

column1: “traditional masculinity ideology has been shown to limit males’ psychological development
column3: result in gender role strain and gender role conflict and negatively influence mental health and physical health

column1: the new “guidelines for psychological practice with boys and men” defines “masculinity ideology” as “a particular constellation of standards that have held sway over large segments of the population
column7: and eschewal of the appearance of weakness.” the report links this ideology to homophobia
column10: and a series of stark statistics: men commit approximately 90 percent of all homicides in the u.s.
column11: they are far more likely than women to be arrested and charged with intimate partner violence in the u.s.
column12: and they are four times more likely than women to die of suicide worldwide.

column1: the guidelines for psychologists outlined in the report include encouraging them to ""recognize that masculinities are constructed based on social
column3: and contextual norms""; ""understand the impact of power
column5: and sexism on the development of boys and men and on their relationships with others""; and ""reduce the high rates of problems boys and men face and act out in their lives such as aggression
column8: and suicide."" apa psychologist jared skillings said parents can play a part
column9: too. he recommended they let their boys know
column10: “it’s ok to not be ok all the time.”'

column1: 175638;instagram;2019-01-10 05:44:10;FALSE;"the time it got hard to believe...in myself
as i get older i think believing in yourself is probably the hardest thing you’ll ever have to do in life.  it’s nothing like overcoming a life-threatening sickness
column3: or abuse (of any kind)...but it’s pretty hard.  and it doesn’t happen overnight...it happens over time...little by little we lose the ability
column5: the gift we’ve been given to believe in ourselves.  and when we do we start to cover-up our flaws or we start to hide them.  yea
column6: i know a thing or two about the struggle of believing in yourself.

column1: i like self-help books.  i like pod casts.  i like healthy living and exercise.  i like healthy friendships and connecting with good people.  i like reading inspiring posts and testimonies.  i like meditation (i’m not good at it 🤷🏽‍♂️ but i like it). i like strengthening my spirituality and i even believe in prayer.  and i even like eating healthy...tho i can’t give up my tacos 🌮 and pizza 🍕...that’s just dumb 🙄 lol.  but no matter how many things i do/we do to help us believe in ourselves this new year...one thing is for sure.  it’s not gonna happen over night.  it took some time to lose that belief...and i’m pretty sure it’s gonna take some time to get it back.  but i believe it will.  and maybe when we start to get that and we’re patient with ourselves
column2: we won’t need to hide or cover-up our flaws and we can just be ourselves.  maybe that’s the ability

أية حماية للعاملات المغربيات في حقول الفراولة بإسبانيا؟

تحول حلم عاملات مغربيات في حقول الفراولة جنوب إسبانيا إلى ما يشبه الكابوس، بعد تعرض بعضهن لصور مختلفة من انتهاكات حقوقهن وصلت حدّ الاعتداء الجنسي. وما كانت هذه القضية تصل إلى علم الرأي العام الوطني والدولي لولا جهود منظمات حقوقية إسبانية وأخرى مغربية دقّت ناقوس الخطر حول الوضعية الصعبة التي تعيشها المئات من العاملات الموسميات.
لقراءة هذا المقال اضغطوا على الرابط في البايو.

column1: i finished the surviving r kelly documentary last night and i am so shocked and outraged at how long this has gone on. my heart goes out to all the victims of his emotional and physical abuse and their families. this man is a predator that feeds of power and in my opinion is far worse than harvey weinstein and needs to be held accountable. i am not trying to compare the two
column3: harvey is being investigated and r kelly is not. we have ourselves to blame in this situation

column5: just because he sings like an angel

column2: i instantly pre-ordered myself a copy! i decided i needed to read this book as soon as it came out 😂 this was another one of my favourite books from 2018 📚 this is the story of the trojan war and homer’s iliad as told by briseis

perhaps every unit i studied referenced the iliad somewhere. it’s a text i always struggled to empathise with or get much out of. i think this is because the stories and characters weren’t ones i could resonate with at all. this was until i read an article that argued that the female characters of the iliad actually drive a significant amount of the plot - i’m not sure how much i agree with this article
column3: but it made me see the women of the iliad in a new light. •

column1: pat barker’s the silence of the girls was my much needed antidote to the issues i had with the iliad. this book highlighted to me that perhaps one of the reasons i struggled to empathise with any emotions of the greek warriors was because they were sexually assaulting women frequently. this definitely taints my view of many of the greek heroes. i’m aware this is a bias
column2: but it’s one i struggle to shake when reading ancient texts. i’m so glad that barker has brought this female experience to the front of her interpretation of the iliad and given these women a voice. this is definitely an iliad for the age of #metoo •

column4: marinade in the depression as it tries to saturate my soul in sadness and despair
column5: or did you just want me to flip my hair
column6: and walk away so you can glare at my ass?  too brass?  to much sass?  why no smile
column7: you ask?  maybe i left it back in my childhood when i still thought people were good.  when i still thought men stood for something more than to look down on a woman and demand she give him more.  maybe i left it on the floor where my tears poured night after night begging for god to restore what some asshole stole from me:  my innocence.  hence the snarl and eye roll you’ll get as you scroll my curves like every other perv who tells me i should smile
column8: instead of giving a fuck about why i’m not.” danielle rutledge

175943;instagram;2019-01-10 13:48:26;FALSE;oooh, i am excited to tell you about this! ♥️ february can be sludgy, but we're warming it up for a night of love and frivolity as we celebrate, discuss and *enjoy* the beautiful and misunderstood genre of the romance novel. ♥️ hosted by firefly founder chris, and romance author allison temple, we'll dive into an unabashed and unapologetic celebration of what romance can be, and is becoming. one part reading (the good parts, we promise), one part q&a and one part open mic, this will be a night for red wine, belly laughs and sudden goosebumps. ♥️ there are so many great questions to dig into! ♥️ what is a romance novel, and why are they so often pushed to the fringes of literary culture? ♥️ what's happening in the world of romance in the wake of #metoo and the rise of self-publishing? ♥️ what about diversity? is the industry growing up from the limited, often-white, heteronormative foundations that started it? column1: 175974;instagram;2019-01-10 14:11:02;TRUE;;i could not have said it better and think everyone should watch it. repost from @caradelevingne- i finished the surviving r kelly documentary last night and i am so shocked and outraged at how long this has gone on. my heart goes out to all the victims of his emotional and physical abuse and their families. this man is a predator that feeds of power and in my opinion is far worse than harvey weinstein and needs to be held accountable. i am not trying to compare the two
column3: harvey is being investigated and r kelly is not. we have ourselves to blame in this situation
column4: i knew of the allegations but failed to try and understand the severity of the situation. i still continued to listen to his music. stop separating art from the artist

column2: and i have been relatively quiet about my personal life but i just want to tell my #followers about something near and dear to me. i have been working as a phone sex operator for some time and recently i've started with a renowned company that i worked for once before. i love my job
column3: but it has also been eye opening and basically a study in #psychology and #sex for me. when i watched #survivingrkelly it was a little triggering and has actually made it a great deal harder to do my job because #rkelly is the tip of the iceberg. when we are told about #pedophilia there is a facade of outrage when i can tell you that people you know want to touch your children
